Bombarding in the name of morality?
NEW YORK – Rhetoric has always been one of the main assets of US President Barack Obama.
Yet, it seems today that his words have trapped him in a dilemma.
After saying in March last year that the United States "would not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against the Syrian people" and mentioning a "red line" that should not be crossed last year, Obama will lose face if he does not react energetically to the murder, attributed to the Syrian regime, of over 1000 civilians using sarin gas.
Of course, the risk of losing face is not a valid reason to attack another country.
But why did Obama get himself into such rhetoric in the first place?
Why this particular line?
US Secretary of State John Kerry is right to qualify the use of gas as "a moral obscenity".
But torturing children, the precursor to civil war two years ago, is just as obscene.
And is killing civilians with chemical products morally more obscene than bombing them, shooting at them, or starving them to death?
It is commonly admitted, since the use of mustard gas during World War I, that some weapons are more immoral than others.
Mass destruction weapons, nuclear bombs in particular, certainly cause more damage and more quickly than conventional weapons.
But is there really a clear moral distinction between killing around 100,000 people with a single atomic bomb in Hiroshima and killing even more people in a single night in Tokyo using incendiary bombs?
Was it more immoral to gas the Jews than to shoot them in mass graves?
One view, defended particularly by Nicholas Kristof of The New York Times, is that a swift punitive action could convince Syrian President Bashar al-Assad to give up using chemical weapons and return to "more conventional means to massacre his people".
In my opinion, this makes no sense.
The question is surely one of massacre, not the methods used.
In any case, moral indignation, however justified it may be, is not a sufficient reason to go to war.
Mao Zedong was responsible for the deaths of more than 40 million Chinese in the 1950s and 1960s.
No sensible person has suggested that a military intervention in China was a good idea.
In the 1980s, Saddam Hussein gasped hundreds of thousands of Iranians and Kurds – with the support of the United States.
Is it therefore a legal issue? The use of chemical weapons constitutes a de facto violation of international conventions, including the Chemical Weapons Convention, which Syria has never signed, and the Geneva Protocol, to which it is a party.
There are therefore valid reasons to consider Assad a war criminal, in which case he should be indicted by the International Criminal Court (ICC), established, incidentally, by a treaty that the United States has never ratified.
But bypassing the United Nations and launching an illegal war to punish an illegal act is not a policy easily defendable.
However, one could argue that the "international community," or Western countries, or the United States as the principal Western power, must surely draw a line somewhere.
How can responsible governments simply turn a blind eye when innocent people are being mass murdered?
Tolerating a genocide is not acceptable.
But exactly where do we draw the line?
How many murders constitute a genocide?
Thousands?
Hundreds of thousands?
Millions?
Or does the number not even come into play?
A genocide is ultimately a matter of intention, there is a will to kill or persecute individuals due to their race, ethnic affiliation, or belief.
In principle, killing ten people for these reasons – or even two – would constitute a form of genocide.
The problem can be approached from a different angle.
The question to consider before intervening militarily in a country is whether this action has a chance to improve the situation, save lives, and make the world a safer place.
Yes, violence against civilians, whether through sarin gas or combat helicopters, is a moral obscenity.
Responding to it involves asking: what is the best solution?
Justice and morality have little to do with such a decision.
Like the action of the ICC, "humanitarian intervention" has a better chance of producing a result in a weak country (for example, Serbia, Mali, or Sierra Leone) than in the case of a major power.
No one would consider missile strikes on China or Russia in the name of human rights defense or to enforce international norms and conventions related to war.
Syria, as many have pointed out, is not Libya or Mali.
It is not a major power either.
However, the civil war raging there has already spilled beyond its borders, involving larger countries, including Iran, Turkey, and Russia.
It is beyond doubt that a regional conflagration would be infinitely worse than the moral obscenities of a civil war.
It is absolutely not certain that American intervention would reduce the risk of a wider conflict.
In fact, some advocates of American intervention – both neoconservatives and "liberal hawks" – seem to want the opposite: they are calling for a war with Iran.
And Obama has probably established a link in his mind between the red line concerning Syria and the one he drew for Iran, perhaps just as thoughtlessly, to prevent it from developing nuclear weapons.
So what are we to expect from American strikes on Syrian targets, when Obama has already indicated that they are not intended to bring down the Syrian regime?
They will not end the civil war.
But a single missile would be enough to make the United States a direct participant in this war, leading to an increase in violence.
Taking this risk to save Obama's honor does not seem particularly wise.
This viewpoint is shared by many Syrians, including among the rebels.
This is the opinion of most Europeans.
And of a majority of Americans.
This may even be Obama's opinion, which is why he is desperately trying to buy time by delegating to the US Congress the authorization to use military force in Syria.
Since taking office, his relations with Congress have been far from easy.
But he needs it more than ever now to cover his back.
